> (...) Your file is invalid JSON (...)

Technically, tsconfig.json is a JSONC file, not JSON. It would be nice if the extension were .jsonc instead, but as long as I can remember tsconfig.json files have always defaulted to having comments (maybe not trailing commas though):

```
❯ bunx tsc --init

Created a new tsconfig.json with:                                                                                       
                                                                                                                     TS 
  target: es2016
  module: commonjs
  strict: true
  esModuleInterop: true
  skipLibCheck: true
  forceConsistentCasingInFileNames: true


You can learn more at https://aka.ms/tsconfig
❯ tail tsconfig.json
    // "noImplicitOverride": true,                       /* Ensure overriding members in derived classes are marked with an override modifier. */
    // "noPropertyAccessFromIndexSignature": true,       /* Enforces using indexed accessors for keys declared using an indexed type. */
    // "allowUnusedLabels": true,                        /* Disable error reporting for unused labels. */
    // "allowUnreachableCode": true,                     /* Disable error reporting for unreachable code. */

    /* Completeness */
    // "skipDefaultLibCheck": true,                      /* Skip type checking .d.ts files that are included with TypeScript. */
    "skipLibCheck": true                                 /* Skip type checking all .d.ts files. */
  }
}
```


> Btw, comments on `tsconfig.json` do not seem to cause any issue with Astro files on Neovim.


If I add either a `//` or `/* ... */` style comment, I'm getting errors in astro files from neovim, similar to if there's a trailing comma. Makes sense if this is using a json parser, but what would it take to use a JSONC parser instead for any jsonc files or known jsonc files like tsconfig.json?

@ivanalejandro0 it looks like there's also a pull request to support comments in tsconfig: https://github.com/wuelnerdotexe/vim-astro/pull/11. It doesn't support inline comments though which is why comments didn't seem to be working for me. Does seem to work if it's on a separate line.

It doesn't look like that library is maintained anymore. The last commit is from 2 years ago and that PR is from over a year ago with no activity. But it looks like astro.vim was added directly to vim with the patch from that pull request around that time with a comment that it was ported from wuelnerdotexe's repo.

I created an issue in the vim repo like you suggested: https://github.com/vim/vim/issues/18141
